First Approach : testing different classifier as is :¶

Here we are in a problem of classification. We want to classify 7 type of trees' Cover. That means, classifier algorithm are recommanded. Here I wanted to try different type classifier, discover how they work, to see how they react, how close (or far) we are from the target. It's more for my personal understanding in a learning process than anything else. Also, the result we catch here will be useful as sample score to compare later.

First we need to split the data set into X train/test and Y test/test :

In [5]:
# Split the Train_set into X and Y
X = df_train.iloc[:,:-1]
Y = df_train.loc[:,'Cover_Type']
In [6]:
# Split of the Train_set into 2 subsets train and test to do more try without submiting to kaggle

We have a majority of Cover Type of kind 1 and 2 that represent more than 85% of the data set.

2. Let's have a look at the features now :¶

We can see that the features matrix can be separated in 3 parts :

  • Columns 1 to 10 are contineous values (Elevation, Slope etc.)
  • Columns 10 to 14 are sparse and it represent different kind of Wilderness
  • Columns 14 to End are sparse and it represent different kind of Soil type

So we gonna look at each one of these part :

Features 1 to 10 (continuous) :¶

In [15]:
X.iloc[:,:10].hist(bins=50,figsize=(18,16))
plt.show()

Here we can see some aberrant values in the features. For example, Hill Shade are not supposed to be <=0. Also Horizontal distance should be only positive. We'll remove those aberrant values later and see if it improves the model.

Compression of Sparse Matrix to improve computation time¶

As the computation takes time, there is an other thing that I tried to do as we have sparse matrix :
I wanted to make a compression of the data to accelarate the computation time. Unfortunately, this method doesn't work with classifier trees nor Random Forest. However I'll show the process as part of my work :

In [17]:
from scipy.sparse import csr_matrix
X_train_sparse = csr_matrix(X_train)
dense_size = np.array(X_train).nbytes
sparse_size = (X_train_sparse.data.nbytes + X_train_sparse.indptr.nbytes + X_train_sparse.indices.nbytes)

sns.barplot(['DENSE', 'SPARSE'], [dense_size, sparse_size])
plt.ylabel('MB')

2. Analizing Impactant Features :¶

From Random Forest :¶

In [162]:
# Sort the features :
importance = pd.DataFrame(rf_clf.feature_importances_)
ind = importance.sort_values(by=0, ascending=False).index
sorted_importance = importance.sort_values(ascending=False,by=0)
features_sorted = pd.DataFrame(index=X_train.columns[ind])
features_sorted['Impact'] = sorted_importance.values

# Treshold >0.1% impact :
best_features = features_sorted[features_sorted.Impact>0.001]

X_train_best = X_train[best_features.index]
X_test_best = X_test[best_features.index]

Improving the model with Hyper Parameters Selection¶

Extra Trees :¶

After many try of tuning, I found the best hyper parameters I could with the imparted time I had. That's with this classifier and parameters that I get my best result on Kaggle with a 0.95576 score.

In [ ]:
# %%timeit -n1 -r1
et_clf = ExtraTreesClassifier(n_estimators=500, bootstrap=False, criterion='entropy'
                              , max_features=54, oob_score=False, n_jobs=-1, random_state=2, class_weight='balanced')
et_clf = et_clf.fit(X.values, Y.values)
et_clf_score_final = et_clf.score(X_test.values, Y_test.values)
print("Extra Tree score = %.4f" %et_clf_score_final)
In [ ]:
